  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Eneza Amani - spreading peace within Kibera slum tribal communities</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Kenya suffered devastating post-election violence following a disputed presidential election result, in 2007. The politically motivated inter-tribal violence, in which 1300 people lost their lives, has led to deep division among tribal groups. Kenyan slums were particularly hard hit as they can represent important power bases for competing politicians. Unless a significant effort is made there is a risk of further violence at the next General Election scheduled for 2012. This violence has added to the risks women face in these slums, who already faced a serious risk of violence at home and on the streets. Building on the lessons learned from a small pilot this project will address inter-tribal conflict and violence against women within Kibera, Kenya&#x2019;s largest slum. Peace education and teaching skills will be improved in church and community-funded schools. The formation of Peace Clubs, School &amp; Family Groups and Women&#x2019;s Groups will enable an inter-generational and mixed gender approach to raise peace awareness and bring together different ethnic groups to undertake local initiatives to reduce violence at the school, family and community level. Making women safer can make whole communities safer, and reduce the risk of communal violence.</narrative>
  </description>
